46. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2027595086
T1  - CHARACTERISTICS OF PATIENTS SEEKING CARE FOR INFERTILITY IN DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC OF CONGO
T3  - 79th Scientific Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Borazjani A.
A1  - Feinberg E.C.
A1  - Ntakwinja M.
A1  - Mukwege D.M. 
Y1  - 2023//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Infertility is prevalent in low-middle income countries, where its intersection with society/culture may result in women being at particular high risk of negative consequences of childlessness [1]. Although the period prevalence of infertility (ie. proportion of a population with infertility at a given point in time) is highest among the WHO African Region, there is data scarcity to guide potential interventions [2]. Our objective was to characterize the demographics and causes of infertility among patients seeking care in Eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to help inform foundations for a sustainable program for fertility care in a resource-limited setting. MATERIALS AND METHODS: This was a cross-sectional descriptive study of patients seeking care for infertility as part of a specialized mission in April 2016 at a tertiary hospital in Bukavu, DRC. Multiple channels (including radio, churches, local organizations) were used to communicate the dates of the mission. Women in heterosexual couples trying to conceive (TTC) for >=2 years were included. Patients underwent history and physical, transvaginal ultrasound, and hysterosalpingography (HSG). Male partners provided a sperm sample for basic sperm count. Data are presented as means with standard deviations or percentages with counts. RESULT(S): A total of 86 patients were included. The mean age was 33.4 (6.1) years, with 33.7% (n=29), 32.6% (n=28), 18.6% (n=16), and 15.1% (n=13) aged <=30, 31-35, 36-40, and >40 years, respectively. Most were nulligravid 66.3% (n=57). The mean duration TTC was 6.5 (2.8) years with 60.5% (n=52) TTC >=5 years. Three-fourths (n=65) reported regular menstrual cycles. Sixty patients underwent HSG, and tubal obstruction was noted in 30% (n=18), hydrosalpinx in 16.7% (n=10), and uterine filling defects in 23.3% (n=14). Forty-three partners provided semen samples, and 11.6% (n=5) and 7.0% (n=3) had azoospermia and oligospermia, respectively. Overall, infertility was most often attributed to tubal disease (30.2%, n=26) followed by polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) (25.6%, n=22), uterine fibroids (20.9%, n=18), unexplained (14%, n=12), and male factor (9.3%, n=8). Over half (58%, n=50) underwent treatment including intrauterine insemination (10.5%, n=9), ovulation induction (16.3%, n=14), or surgical management (31.4%, n=27). CONCLUSION(S): Infertility was most often attributed to tubal disease. A large proportion of patients were TTC for 5 or more years, suggesting a lack of access to fertility care in DRC. The most common causes of infertility (tubal disease, PCOS, uterine fibroids) observed were those with the best prognosis showing great promise for future intervention. The high prevalence of tubal disease demonstrates opportunity for better public health education on the link between sexually transmitted infection and infertility. These data provide a springboard for future work aimed at primary prevention, diagnosis, and treatment of infertility in resource-limited settings. IMPACT STATEMENT: Among infertile couples in DRC, causes were most often attributed to tubal disease, PCOS, or uterine fibroids. SUPPORT: None REFERENCES: [1] Ombelet et al. "Infertility and the provision of infertility medical services in developing countries". Human Reproduction Update. (2008). [2] World Health Organization. "Infertility prevalence estimates: 1990-2021". (2023).Copyright © 2023
