99. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638513639
T1  - Effect of endometriosis on the IVF/ICSI success outcomes!
T3  - Royal College of Obstretriscians and Gynaecologists World Congress, RCOG 2022. London United Kingdom.
A1  - Shingshetty L.
A1  - Retto A.
A1  - Akhtar M. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introduction: Endometriosis is defined as the presence of endometrial-like tissue outside the uterus, which induces a chronic inflammatory reaction. (ESHRE 2013). As per ESHRE guidelines, the exact prevalence is unknown and is estimated at approximately up to 2-10 %, however with a surge of up to 50% in women with endometriosis. In order to enhance their chances of having a child, these women are more likely to seek assistance from the fertility units for achieving conception. This study aims to estimate the effect of endometriosis on success rates of IVF/ICSI cycles as compared to women without endometriosis. Material(s) and Method(s): This is a retrospective observational study conducted at St. Mary's Hospital, Manchester, UK, including women who underwent IVF/ICSI cycles from January 2013 till December 2016 over four years. A total of 4369 IVF/ICSI cycles were performed over this period. Women were categorised according to the presence of endometriosis as a sole significant contributory factor for infertility, endometriosis with other factors for infertility like tubal pathology, anovulatory cycles, male factor and finally, women without any evidence of endometriosis. Diagnosis of endometriosis was based on symptoms, Ultrasound or laparoscopic findings. A total of 182 women had endometriosis in the range of minimal to mild disease, moderate and severe disease as per ASRM classification for endometriosis. Women were compared according to the stages of endometriosis, and outcomes measured were live birth rate, miscarriage, biochemical pregnancy, failed fertilisation, poor response, duration of ovarian stimulation and the total gonadotrophin dose required for IVF/ ICSI cycles. Result(s): Women with endometriosis generally had poor success outcomes in terms of the number of oocytes retrieved (6.8 vs 9.7) and increased risk of failed fertilisation (9% vs 5.6%; p-value 0.04) compared to women with no disease. Those with the moderate-severe disease were affected significantly as the live birth rate was much lower (13.1% vs 33.29%; p-value0.000068) than women with no endometriosis. The live birth rates were comparable between women with minimal-mild endometriosis (34.5%) and women without endometriosis. (33.29%) Conclusion(s): Endometriosis is a disease that has a detrimental influence over the success rates of ART (Artificial Reproductive Technologies) cycles. It further deteriorates the chances of conception with the severity of the disease. Early diagnosis and prompt initiation of treatment may benefit these women rather than advising them to continue their efforts for natural conception for 12 months as per the NICE guidance before starting investigations and management.
