T1  - An Incidental Finding of Isolated Fallopian tube Torsion in Adolescent: A Case Report and Review of Literature
T3  - The AAGL 2021 50th Global Congress on MIGS. Austin United States.
A1  - Felimban H.M.
A1  - Alajani D.M. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Study Objective: An Incidental finding of Isolated Fallopian Tube Torsion (IFTT) in adolescent with unique Ultrasound Findings: A Case Report and Review of Literature. Design(s): case report and review of literature. Setting(s): case report and review of literature. Patients or Participants: A 17-years-old single girl presented to the emergency department with a sudden moderate to severe right iliac fossa pain that had lasted for more than one day. Pain is associated with nausea and multiple episodes of non-projectile vomiting consisting of food content. No history of fever, diarrhea and loss of appetite. Transabdominal ultrasound showed both ovaries are polycystic in appearance measures Right ovary:34 x 18 x 38 mm, left ovary: 34 x 31 x 34 mm and both ovaries were seen with normal color doppler flow. There was a simple cystic structure seen anterior to the uterus measures: 65 x 49 mm with normal color doppler seen. Intervention(s): Diagnostic laparoscopy, detorsion and partial salpingectomy. Measurements and Main Results: Post laparoscopy. Conclusion(s): We present one rare case of IFTT. Ultrasound is a helpful tool for the recognition of this gynecological emergency. IFTT presentation with non-specific pictures should be considered in the differential diagnosis of all females regardless of the age in which they represent lower abdominal pain with a pathological adnexal structure and normal ovaries. Urgent Laparoscopic intervention is the gold standard diagnostic and treatment method.Copyright © 2021
