126. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 635242703
T1  - How appropriately women with fertility issues are referred for hysterosalpingography?
T3  - RCOG National Trainees Conference, NTC 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Steshenko A.
A1  - Hanna L. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Introduction Hysterosalpingography (HSG) should be offered to women investigated for sub-fertility to screen for tubal occlusion as a first-line test to exclude tubal factor infertility. It is a reliable test and less invasive than laparoscopy. According to NICE clinical guideline [CG156] HSG should be only requested for women who have no risk factors, are not known to have previous ectopic pregnancies, pelvic inflammatory disease, pelvic surgery or endometriosis etc. Since the number of referrals for HSG has increased, we conducted an audit to study the appropriateness of referral for HSG. Methods It was a retrospective review of medical records where patients were investigated for sub-fertility and referred for hysterosalpingogram as part of clinical investigation from 1st November 2017 till 31st October 2018. NICE clinical guideline [CG156] was used as auditable standard. Results Only 13 (15.1%) from 86 patients met NICE guideline criteria for HSG referral. From 73 (84.9%) patients who did not meet criteria for HSG, 33 patients had anovulatory cycles and 19 women were unable to conceive because of their male partner had abnormal semen count. Remaining 21 women who did not meet referral criteria for HSG had other causes (previous Caesarean section, myomectomy, hydrosalpinx). Conclusion The audit demonstrated that the number of patients requiring HSG was low. Several strategies can be implemented to improve appropriate referral for HSG such as training of doctors working in gynaecology clinic, developing new referral proforma for HSG, introducing Hystero Contrast Sonography (HyCoSy) to replace HSG.
