159. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2006873902
T1  - ETIOLOGIES OF SUBFERTILITY AND PREGNANCY OUTCOMES AMONG LESBIAN WOMEN UNDERGOING DONOR SPERM INTRAUTERINE INSEMINATION
T3  - Sixty-Eighth Annual Meeting of the Pacific Coast Reproductive Society. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Kim A.S.
A1  - Hall J.M.
A1  - Ho N.J.
A1  - Dhesi A.S.
A1  - Baker M.B.
A1  - Jabara S. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background: Utilization of assisted reproduction by lesbian women has increased over the past decade. Despite this, limited studies exist to guide fertility care for this growing patient population.1 Many practitioners expect that lesbians should experience similar or greater success with assisted reproduction than their heterosexual counterparts, however some studies suggest that lesbians may be subfertile. Further evidence regarding underlying etiologies of subfertility and assisted reproductive outcomes in lesbian women is needed to optimize care. Objective(s): To compare the etiologies of subfertility and pregnancy outcomes of donor sperm intrauterine insemination (DS-IUI) cycles in lesbian women and heterosexual women. Material(s) and Method(s): Retrospective chart review. T-tests were used to determine statistical significance for continuous variables. Chi-square or Fisher's exact tests were used for categorical variables. P <= 0.05 used to determine statistical significance. Result(s): A total of 264 subjects who presented for DS-IUI at two affiliated medical centers from 2016-2019 were included: 146 coupled lesbian women, 45 single heterosexual women, and 73 coupled heterosexual women. Race, body mass index (BMI), and early follicular phase FSH were similar between all three groups. Lesbians were significantly younger (33.1 +/- 4.5 years) than single (37.8 +/- 3.5 years, p<0.001) and coupled heterosexuals (34.5 +/- 3.7 years, p=0.02). Lesbians did not have an increased prevalence of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) (OR 2.12, 95% CI 1, 4.52, p=0.6811) nor diminished ovarian reserve (DOR) (OR 2.86, 95% CI 1.44, 5.64, p=0.0908). Fewer lesbians reported a history of sexually transmitted infection (5.5% versus 18%, p=0.03). Lesbians also had less tubal disease (defined as an abnormal radiographic finding in at least one fallopian tube on hysterosalpingogram) (7.5% versus 16%, p=0.04). There was no difference in the age-adjusted number of DS-IUI cycles to achieve clinical pregnancy between lesbian (4.6 cycles) and single women (4.0 cycles, p=0.06), but coupled heterosexuals (3.0 cycles, p=0.06) required 24% fewer DS-IUI cycles to achieve pregnancy than lesbians (OR 0.76, 95% CI 0.66-0.9, p=0.0007). Conclusion(s): This study is the first in the United States to compare both the etiologies of subfertility and pregnancy outcomes of lesbian women and heterosexual women undergoing DS-IUI. When compared to their heterosexual counterparts, our data reveal less tubal disease and no increased prevalence of PCOS or DOR in lesbian women. Interestingly, lesbian women required more DS-IUI cycles to achieve clinical pregnancy than coupled heterosexual women. Support: None References: 1. Tarin JJ, Garcia-Perez MA, Cano A. Deficiencies in reporting results of lesbians and gays after donor intrauterine insemination and assisted reproductive technology treatments: a review of the first emerging studies. Reprod Biol Endocrinol. 2015;13:52.Copyright © 2020
