160. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2002643651
T1  - Progressive alopecia, recalcitrant acne, and hirsutism as the presenting signs of a Leydig cell tumor of the ovary
T3  - American Academy of Dermatology 2019 Annual Meeting. District of Columbia United States.
A1  - Edelman A.
A1  - Burton S.K.
A1  - Callen J.P. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Case Report: A 67-year-old woman with a history of rosacea presented with recalcitrant cystic acne. Additionally, the patient reported a 2-year history of gradual scalp hair loss and an increase in facial hair. There was no personal or family history of alopecia, hirsutism, or hyperandrogenism. Physical examination revealed excessive hair on her upper lip, chin, and lateral cheeks. She also had severe frontoparietal hair loss, thinning on the crown, and nodulocystic acne on her chin and cheeks. Laboratory tests showed markedly elevated levels of total testosterone (539 ng/dL), free testosterone (61.8 pg/mL) and DHEA-S (258 ug/dL). Abdominal CT scan showed normal appearing adrenal glands. MRI of the pelvis revealed a 2.5 x 2.3cm ovoid structure off the superior aspect of the uterus, concerning for a leiomyoma, an ovarian or adnexal process. A pelvic ultrasound revealed a right sided sterile hydrosalpinx. The patient had a diagnostic laparoscopy, salpingo-oophorectomy, hysteroscopy and dilation and curettage. The right ovary showed a 2cm white solid nodule. Histopathological examination and immunohistochemistry confirmed a diagnosis of Leydig cell tumor. Three months after surgical removal of the tumor, the patient's testosterone levels decreased with some improvements in her hirsutism and acne. Discussion(s): It can be challenging to diagnose postmenopausal hyperandrogenism, as symptoms of alopecia and hirsutism are often dismissed as mere cosmetic complaints in patients with normal hormonal changes seen with aging. Recommended tests in any woman presenting with alopecia and signs of virilization include a detailed clinical history, physical examination, complete blood count, thyroid stimulating hormone, dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEA-S), and testosterone levels. In the presence of recent onset of hirsutism in a postmenopausal woman, with or without virilization, the possibility of an adrenal or ovarian tumor should be considered. Other causes of hyperandrogenism, particularly with signs of virilization, should be ruled out, such as drugs, pituitary disorders, Cushing syndrome, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, ovarian hyperthecosis, hyperandrogenic insulin-resistant acanthosis nigricans syndrome, and ectopic production of hormones by tumors. Among ovarian tumors, only 5% are virilizing; they include Sertoli-Leydig cell tumors, hilar cell tumors, lipoid cell tumors, and adrenal rest tumors. Leydig cell tumors are a rare type of sex cord-stromal tumor of the ovary that primary occur in young women and account for only 0.5% of all ovarian tumors. These tumors mainly secrete testosterone, which can lead to symptoms of virilization.
