179. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2002370640
T1  - Experience of combination of saline infusion with tubal contrast in sonography for subfertility evaluation at the largest public gynaecological tertiary referral centre in Singapore
T3  - The World Congress For Ultrasound. Melbourne Convention and Exhibition Centre, Melbourne Australia.
A1  - Tan S.M.A.S.M.A.
A1  - Ong C.L.C.L.
A1  - Teo S.Y.S.Y. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction: Fallopian tube patency testing is the current standard of care for subfertility evaluation and commonly performed at our institution. Evidence supports HyFoSy as an alternative to hysterosalpingography (HSG) for outpatient tubal evaluation and it may be superior to saline hysterosalpingo-contrast sonography (HyCoSy) in excluding tubal occlusion. Our current practice is to combine HyFoSy in tubal assessment with saline infusion for uterine cavity assessment in a single study. Aim(s): To describe our combination HyFoSy-saline infusion protocol, pathology detected in our local population, tolerability and occurrence of pregnancy post-procedure. Methodology: Retrospective review of HyFoSy-saline infusion studies performed at our institution in 2017. Result(s): Study is performed between 7-14 days of the menstrual cycle. Targeted history and informed consent are obtained. Standard ultrasound pelvis is performed initially to look for uterine and adnexal masses and quantification of ovarian cysts. An intracervical catheter is then introduced and the uterine cavity is distended with sterile normal saline to visualise endometrial cavity structural anomalies and lesions. Finally foam contrast is instilled and flow within the fallopian tubes and spillage is observed in real time. Of 100 women, no cases were abandoned due to technical difficulty, severe pain or vasovagal episode. Three women (3%) cited significant pain with a median pain score of 5 and one (1%) required referral to the emergency department. In 3 women (3%), intravasation of tubal contrast occurred. Mean study time was 18 minutes. Mean age was 34 years. Seventy-seven women (77%) were nulliparous at the time of the study with 62 (62%) being nulligravida. Thirty-six (36%) had previous uterine intervention with 25 (25%) being previous D&C of which 6 (6%) were for pregnancy termination. Seven women (7%) had a history of miscarriage or ectopic pregnancy. Thirty-three (33%) studies found intra-cavitary findings: 15 (15%) demonstrated adhesions and 21 (21%) endometrial polyps; no submucosal fibroids. Ninety-four women (94%) had at least 1 patent tube with both tubes being patent in 76 (76%). Four women (4%) had salpingectomy due to previous EP or ovarian torsion. Hydrosalpinx was found in 3 women (3%). Thirty-two women (32%) had polycystic ovaries. Nine women (9%) gave birth successfully within 1 year of the study; 5 through assisted reproduction. Conclusion(s): Combination of saline infusion with tubal contrast in sonography for subfertility evaluation offers improved visualisation of uterine cavity abnormalities whilst leveraging on the potential advantages of HyFoSy over HyCoSy. A small minority experience significant pain or contrast intravasation.Copyright © 2019
