194. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001201945
T1  - Evaluation of Laparoscopic Ovarian Drilling by Harmonic Scalpel versus Monopolar Drilling Needle in Cases of Clomiphene Citrate Resistant Polycystic Ovarian Response
T3  - 47th American Association of Gynecologic Laparoscopists (AAGL) Global Congress on Minimally Invasive Gynecologic Surgery (MIGS). MGM Grand Conference Center, Las Vegas United States.
A1  - Roy K.K.
A1  - Maddirala H.
A1  - Kumar S.
A1  - Singhal S.
A1  - Meena J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objective: To compare the efficacy of ovarian drilling by harmonic scalpel versus drilling by unipolar electocautery in terms of biochemical response, ovulation and pregnancy rate. To find out the occurrence of any post operative peritubal and periovarian adhesions. Design(s): Prospective randomized clinical study involving patients of PCOS resistant to clomiphene citrate. Setting(s): Tertiary care referral hospital (AIIMS) with apex research centre. Patient(s): Infertile patients of PCOS resistant to clomiphene citrate having normal tubal patency and normal husband semen parameters. Intervention(s): For ovarian drilling, in group I patients, harmonic scalpel (Ethicon ultracission germany) shear was used and in group II patients, insulated unipolar electrocautery needle electrode was used. In both the groups a total of 5 punctures per ovary were created. After drilling the ovary was allowed to cool in a pool of saline to prevent excessive heat trauma. Measurements/Results: Sixty cases were recruited between February 2016 to December 2016. All patients were randomly allocated into two equal groups. There was no statistical difference between the two groups in terms of clinical and biochemical response. Although group I had shown higher pregnancy rate and ovulation rate compared to group II, it was not statistically significant. The patients who ovulated following drilling had greater decrease in serum concentration of LH than those who did not ovulate. Post operative adhesions could be assessed in 31% of the patients in both the groups. Significant difference in postoperative adhesion was found in group II patients compared to group I (21% versus 0%). Conclusion(s): A novel technique of using harmonic scalpel with less destruction of the ovarian capsule for ovarian drilling showed better clinical and biochemical response, higher pregnancy rate and no post operative adhesions formation. This study encourages larger randomized trials.Copyright © 2018
