201. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 618976982
T1  - Assessment of therapeutic benefit of Hysterosalpingo- Contrast-Sonography (HyCoSy) in sub-fertile women to increase the chance of spontaneous or assisted reproductive technology pregnancies
T3  - 68th Annual Scientific Meeting of the Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Radiologists, RANZCR 2017. Perth, WA Australia.
A1  - Pearce S.
A1  - Lo G.
A1  - Murphy A.
A1  - Li E. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Purpose: To assess if hysterosalpingo-contrast-sonography (HyCoSy) can influence the induction of spontaneous or assisted reproductive technology (ART) pregnancies. The audit also assesses the tolerability and complication rate of the procedure. Age of the patient at HyCoSy, additional pelvic pathology, fallopian tubal patency, and parity were also collected to assess their ability to influence fertility prognosis. Method(s): Design: Retrospective audit with review of the literature. Setting(s): 120 sub-fertile women underwent a HyCoSy between 2013 and 2016 at a subspecialist outpatient ultrasound practice, Western Ultrasound for Women, for diagnostic assessment of tubal patency. Intervention(s): Patients were called in December 2016 for a phone interview to assess pregnancy outcomes and previous parity. This was compared with the reported outcomes of the HyCoSy. Result(s): Fallopian tubes were bilaterally patent in 104/120 patients (87%), had single patency in 13/120 (11%) and were bilaterally blocked in 3/120 (2.5%). Pregnancy occurred in 44/104 (42%) with bilaterally patent tubes, 9/13 (69%) with single patency, and 3 (100%) with blocked tubes, in the follow up period. 40/120 (33%) conceived spontaneously. An additional 20/120 (17%) conceived with support of ART. A total of 60/120 women (50%) conceived during the follow-up period with a mean time of 5.9 months, mode of 3 months, and median of 4 months. The time to pregnancy was faster from spontaneous (3.8 months) compared to ART (7.7 months). 62/120 had additional reported pelvic pathologies with polycystic ovaries, fibroids, and adenomyosis being the most common. There was no decrease in pregnancy rates in women with pathologies found (53% with pathology, 43.3% without). In patients >=35 years 20/41 (49%) conceived and 39/79 (49%) patients <35 years conceived. Thirty-two women had pregnancies prior to the HyCoSy. 21/ 32 (66%) achieved a pregnancy post-procedure. 17/21 (81%) were spontaneous and 4/21 (19%) were assisted. 4/120 (3%) experience side-effects with 2 experiencing severe vaso-vagal reactions (requiring rest for 20 min at the clinic) and two experiencing severe discomfort. Conclusion(s): HyCoSy referrals are indicated in women with unexplained subfertility and the procedure is likely to influence the induction of pregnancy in this group as pregnancy has occurred in a substantial percentage of cases. It has good tolerability with limited complications. These findings are in agreement with the current available literature.1-3 Previous parity is a positive prognostic factor for future pregnancies. Age and the presence of additional pelvic pathologies did not alter prognosis. HyCoSy may play an important therapeutic role in the management of sub-fertile patients.
