244. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 615029221
T1  - Evaluation of proximal tubal blockage by hysterosalpingogram
T3  - FERTILITY 2015: British Fertility Society Association of Clinical Embryologists Society for Reproduction and Fertility. Birmingham United Kingdom.
A1  - Karasu T.
A1  - Hatsiopoulou O.
A1  - Skull J. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Objective: Tubal disease is the cause of subfertility in approximately 30% of women and 10-25% of these are due to proximal tubal obstruction. The most common assessment of the fallopian tube is done by the hysterosalpingography (HSG). If abnormal findings are detected on HSG then a laparoscopy and dye test is performed. In addition to the tubal patency assessment, the external appearance of the tube, the fimbria and the entire pelvis can be assessed. The incidence of adhesions and endometriosis in infertile women is not low. These findings can be treated at the surgery and thereby increase the chances of a pregnancy. The aim of this study was to present the diagnostic findings, the tubal patency rates and the reproductive outcome in patients with proximal tubal obstruction (PTO) on HSG followed by laparoscopic surgery. Relevance: Correct assessment of the female pelvis is paramount for women with abnormal HSG findings. Method(s): This was a retrospective study at a University Teaching Hospital. 41 women had PTO demonstrated on HSG from February 2011 to October 2013, who underwent laparoscopic surgery. Main outcome measures were the confirmed tubal blockage during the following laparoscopy and the immediate success of hysteroscopic tubal cannulation (HTC) evidenced by the laparoscopic chromopertubation +/- reproductive outcome and additional findings during laparoscopy. Outcome(s): 31.7% (13/41) had bilateral tubal patency and 63.4% (26/41) had confirmed tubal blockage during laparoscopy. Successful HTC was achieved in 12/23 (52.2%). 36.6% (15/41) had additional findings like adhesions, polycystic ovaries, endometriosis and ovarian cyst which were treated. No complications occurred. Following surgery, 6/41women (14.6%) conceived spontaneously and 5/41 (12.2%) following IVF treatment. Discussion(s): Laparoscopic assessment of the tubes after an abnormal HSG provides additional information of the pelvis and may change the management of the patient. Ultimately, this may increase the chances of a successful pregnancy.
