T1  - Abnormal ureteral position with adherant ovary
T3  - 44th Global Congress of Minimally Invasive Gynecology, AAGL 2015. Las Vegas, NV United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Woods S.M.
A1  - Dhari A.S.
A1  - Martin D.C. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Study Objective: Describe a case where retroperitoneal ureterolysis was needed to restore normal anatomy of an abnormal ureteral position when the ovary and broad ligament were densely adherent to the posterior uterus. Design(s): Case study. Setting(s): Private Hospital, University physicians. Patient(s): 39 year-old G1, P0 with polycystic ovary syndrome, abnormal uterine bleeding, chronic anemia, 1,220 gram leiomyoma, abdominal fullness, and dysmenorrhea. History was significant for myomectomies, iron transfusions, and medroxyprogesterone trial. Ultrasound and saline infusion sonohysterogram revealed an enlarged uterus, multiple leiomyomata, polycystic left ovary, and non-visualization of the right ovary. Endometrial biopsy noted disordered proliferative endometrium. Intervention(s): She underwent laparoscopic partial lysis of adhesions followed by laparotomy, extensive enterolyis with serosal repair, right retroperitoneal ureterolysis, total abdominal hysterectomy and bilateral salpingectomy. Estimated blood loss was 750 milliliters. Operative time was 5 hours, 9 minutes. Measurements and Main Results: Intra-operative findings were significant for a 1,220 gram fibroid uterus and diffuse bowel, ovarian, uterine, and broad ligament adhesions with distorted anatomy. The dense broad ligament adhesions to the posterior uterus resulted in the right ureter being adjacent to the posterior uterus. The mid-pelvic ureter was deviated toward the midline. After initial lysis to restore normal anatomy, the ureter and broad ligament remained adherent near the uterine isthmus. Retroperitoneal ureterolysis was used to move the ureter into a normal position. Final pathology revealed leiomyomata, adenomyosis, proliferative endometrium, fibrovascular serosal adhesions, and benign fallopian tubes. Post-operative anemia did not require transfusion. She was discharged on post-operative day 2. Conclusion(s): Anatomy should always be restored prior to proceeding with hysterectomy. Restoring the ovarian position does not always restore the broad ligament and ureteral positions. Retroperitoneal dissection and ureterolysis were needed in this case to restore the ureter to its normal path. Findings of a densely adherent ovary to the uterus should raise awareness of potential abnormal positioning of the broad ligament and ureter. (Figure Presented).
