247. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72093705
T1  - Study of laparoscopic findings in patients with chronic pelvic pain in Central Women's Hospital, Yangon, Myanmar
T3  - 24th Asian and Oceanic Congress of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, AOCOG 2015. Sarawak Malaysia.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Lynn N.E.M.
A1  - Thein H.T.S.
A1  - Mya W.W. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Introduction: Living with any chronic pain carries physical, mental and heavy economic and social price. Accurate diagnosis and effective management from the first presentation may help to reduce the disruption of the women's life and may avoid an endless succession of referrals, investigations and operations. Chronic pelvic pain is a common disorder of women that often presents a diagnostic dilemma. Laparoscopy in chronic pelvic pain pertains to one of the most important examination procedures for its high specificity and sensitivity. This study is to study laparoscopic findings in patients with chronic pelvic pain in Central Women's Hospital, Yangon, Myanmar. Method(s): A hospital based descriptive study of the patients with chronic pelvic pain from 1st July 2011 to 28th February 2013. Result(s): Out of (966) out-patients attended to the hospital, chronic pelvic pain patients account for (246) cases, (25%). Among (6763) cases admitted to the hospital, (96) cases were due to chronic pelvic pain. The incidence of chronic pelvic pain patients was (14.2) per (1000) admissions. The majority of patients in this study were married (89%) and nulliparity (66%). Most of the chronic pelvic pain patients undergoing laparoscopy have symptoms of acyclic lower abdominal pain (81%) and congestive dysmenorrhoea (69%), followed by spasmodic dysmenorrhoea (61%), and deep dyspareunia, (25%). At laparoscopy, the findings were pelvic adhesion (50%), endometriosis (36%), pelvic inflammatory disease (33%), pelvic congestion (28%), endometriotic cyst (25%), ovarian cyst and polycystic ovary (22%), uterine fibroid (14%), no abnormal finding (11%) and tuberculosis (3%). In the ultrasound, the findings were normal in 28 cases (78%), but in the laparoscopy, only four cases (11%) had normal findings. The complications were nausea and vomiting (22%), post-operative shoulder tip pain (14%) and surgical emphysema (3%). Conclusion(s): Laparoscopy is the gold standard for diagnosis of chronic pelvic pain as it can give the accurate diagnosis by direct visualization of the abdominal cavity. The study for diagnosis of the different types of pelvic pathology in patients with chronic pelvic pain can tailor up the treatment options according to the diagnosis.
