254. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71912207
T1  - Experience of two-dimensional hysterosalpingocontrast sonography with sonovue contrast for assessment of tubal patency in women with subfertility
T3  - RCOG World Congress 2015. Brisbane, QLD Australia.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Mohanraj P.
A1  - Briggs S.
A1  - Ahluwalia A. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Introduction Transvaginal hysterosalpingo-contrast sonography (TV-HyCoSy) can contribute to accurate diagnosis of tubal patency. National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) recommends HyCoSy to be used as a screening tool for tubal patency as an alternative to hysterosalpingography in women who are not known to have comorbidities (such as pelvic inflammatory disease, previous ectopic pregnancy or endometriosis). With Echovist being withdrawn from the market the only other contrast agent being used for HyCoSy is SonoVue. This procedure is costeffective, less invasive, safe and side effects are rare. Methods Retrospective analysis of women who underwent HyCoSy during the period from 1 January 2011 to 30 July 2014 by a single operator along with Sonologist was analysed. All patients underwent transvaginal HyCoSy by inserting a cervical catheter and a solution with sulphur hexafluoride bubbles (SonoVue) was injected into the uterine cavity and tubes while contrast-tuned imaging was applied. Results Out of 137 women who underwent this procedure, three cases were excluded due to cervical stenosis and hydrosalphinx. On analysis of the remaining 134 patients, tubes were absent 4 (2.98%); hydrosalphinx in 2 (1.49%); tubes not identified in 5 (3.73%); tubes not seen in 1 (0.74%). Fibroids identified in 11 (8.20%); bicornuate uterus 1 (0.74%). Endometrial polyps were visualised in 3 (2.23%), increased endometrial thickness in 2 (1.49%). Bilateral polycystic ovaries in 23 (17.16%); unilateral polycystic appearance in 10 (7.46%); either ovary not seen in 7 (5.22%); suggestive of endometriosis in 3 (2.23%); other cysts 4 (2.98%). None of the patients developed any immediate complication from the procedure. Of these 98% women had high satisfaction rate following this procedure. Conclusion Transvaginal contrast sonography is less invasive and well tolerated and helps obtain information on cervical stenosis, uterine cavity, tubes and adnexal pathology. It is useful in triaging cases for more invasive testing.
