A1  - Owen E. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Introduction As part of sub-fertility work-up, women are offered a lap & dye if co-morbidities are identified in their history (e.g. dysmenorrhoea) or an abnormal HSG. In our unit lap & dye is also offered when there is a normal HSG but no conception following 2 cycles of SO/IUI. During the lap & dye; minor surgery (mild endometriosis ablation, adhesiolysis) or major surgery (mod/severe endometriosis ablation, tubal surgery) may be carried out. A subsequent 3 month post surgery follow up appointment is made on the assumption that there is a "good" chance of the patient falling pregnant in this time. If bilateral tubal damage is identified, the patient is referred directly for IVF. Methods All lap & dye patients taken from the theatre procedure book over a 2 year period from Jan 2010 to Dec 2011. Patients with anovulation or severe male factor were excluded. Results 107 cases were identified, 89 notes were collected and analysed. The median age for the group was 32 years with a median sub-fertility time of 3 years and 4 months. 47% (42/89) of patients had a HSG prior to laparoscopy. 38% (16/42) had an abnormal test and 61% (26/42) had failed SO/IUI. At lap & dye, pathology was confirmed in 69% of cases (61/89). Minor surgery was performed in 62% (38/61). The 3 month conception rate was 18% for this group. Major surgery was performed in 31% (19/61), there were no conceptions in the 3 months post surgery. When no pathology was identified at lap & dye (28/89-31%) the conception rate was 21% at 3 months following surgery. Discussion/Conclusion In women with a median sub-fertility length of 3+ years with either no or minimal pathology, 1 in 5 conceived in the 3 months following surgery.
