295. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71165256
T1  - Preapoptotic sperm rate in ejaculate and intrauterine insemination success rate in patients with unexplained infertility
T3  - International Federation of Fertility Societies 21st World Congress on Fertility and Sterility and the 69th Annual Meeting of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, IFFS-ASRM 2013. Boston, MA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Boyraz G.
A1  - Gunalp S.
A1  - Menkveld R.
A1  - Sokmensuer L.K.
A1  - Bozdag G.
A1  - Esinler I. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: The parameters measured in the standard semen analysis may be insufficient for exact differentiation between fertile and infertile men. In that context, determining the apoptotic cells may be an alternative to predict treatment success. Neverthless, apoptotic cells can be determined by Annexin V molecule which has a calcium-dependent binding to phosphatidylserine that have appeared on the cell surface. We assume that the high rate of apoptotic sperm in ejaculate may play a role on the etiology of unexplained infertility. DESIGN: Prospective cohort study. MATERIALS AND METHODS: Patients with unexplained infertility treated by ovulation induction with exogenous gonadotropin and intrauterine insemination were consecutively enrolled between March-2012 and December-2012 in our department (n=94). The exclusion criteria were presence of tubal occlusion with hysterosalpingography, severe male factor or anovulation. To determine the proapoptotic sperm rate, following a 3-6 days of sexual abstinence, the ejaculate from patients was stained with annexin V (Annexin V-FITC Apoptosis Detection Kit-Santa Cruz Biotechnology,CA, USA). Sperm morphology was also analysed according to Kruger's strict criteria. RESULT(S): The mean female and male ages were 28.3 and 32.4, respectively. Thirteen of 94 women (13.8%) succeed to achieve after intrauterine insemination. The annexin V-positive sperm rate was found to be 20.0% in the whole group. When compared with the women failing to conceive, annexin V-positive sperm rate was comparable among patients who achieved pregnancy (20.8% vs 15.7%, respectively). Those rates were not effected by male age, tobacco use and sperm morphology. CONCLUSION(S): Although there is a trend of higher preapoptotic sperm rate in patients failing to get pregnant with insemination, the difference did not reach statistical significance. The validity of annexin-v for predicting pregnancy should be confirmed with further studies having larger sample sizes.
