297. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71136118
T1  - Hysterosalpingo contrast sonography (HyCoSy) in a district general outpatient fertility clinic
T3  - RCOG World Congress 2013. Liverpool United Kingdom.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Ioannou E.
A1  - Kirk E.
A1  - Lieberman G. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Objectives To evaluate the indication and findings in women booked for outpatient hysterosalpingo contrast sonography (HyCoSy) in the fertility clinic of a district general hospital. Methods Women booked for HyCoSy were identified from the hospital appointment system. The computerised report generated at the time of the examination was reviewed along with the case notes when necessary. Data collected included: maternal age, type of infertility (primary or secondary), duration of infertility, findings at the time of the transvaginal ultrasound examination (TVS), result of the tubal patency at the time of HyCoSy, planned subsequent management and the results of any other surgical interventions performed to improve chance of conception. Results During the study period, 124 women were booked for HyCoSy. Maternal age ranged from 21 to 44 years, median 33 years, 82.3% had primary infertility and 17.7% secondary infertility. 118/124 (95.2%) underwent HyCoSy. Reasons for not performing a HyCoSy included: an inability to cannulate the cervix, the woman already being pregnant, no semen analysis result and abnormalities on the TVS requiring laparoscopy. 25/124 (20.2%) women were found to have pathology on the TVS prior to the HyCoSy. Eight women were found to have endometrial polyps, five women had endometriotic or dermoid cysts, eight women had polycystic ovaries, two women had a hydrosalpinx and two women appeared to have an ovary adherent to either the pelvic side wall or uterus. At the time of HyCoSy, 87/118 (73.7%) had bilateral patent tubes, 24/118 (20.4%) had a unilateral patent tube and 7 (5.9%) had bilateral blocked tubes. Conclusions HyCoSy is a valuable diagnostic tool in the outpatient investigation of the infertile woman. In <5% of cases it was not possible to evaluate tubal patency on the day of the clinic visit. In 20% of woman additional pathology was detected on TVS at the time of the HyCoSy.
