N2  - Objectives To measure our practice against the standards of National Institute of Clinical Excellence guidelines in view of offering Chlamydia screening prior to uterine instrumentation and the use of Hysterosalpingography (HSG) in favour of Laparoscopy for women who are not known to have co-morbidities such as Pelvic Inflammatory Disease, previous ectopic pregnancy or endometriosis. Methods Retrospective audit of 58 consecutive HSG cases identified from a radiological database. Results Chlamydia screening prior HSG was achieved in all cases. Median Body Mass Index of patients was 26.4 with inter-quartile range (IQR) 23.3-32, median age was 30.5 with IQR 26-33, primary infertility constituted for 52% of all cases of infertility, median length of infertility was 2 years with IQR 1-2 and the most common cause of infertility was Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (31%). Out of all HSG examinations 84.5% (49/58) identified patent fallopian tubes and 19% (11/58) of all patients underwent Laparoscopy and Dye test. Most common identified pathology was endometriosis (46%). Conclusions Our audit identified that our practice of offering Chlamydia screening and use of Hysterosalpingography meet the national standards.
