321. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70526052
T1  - The role of laparoscopic ovarian drilling in ovulation induction for polycystic ovary syndrome: Audit of five years experience from a district general hospital setting in UK
T3  - 27th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE 2011. Stockholm Sweden.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Akhtar M.A.
A1  - Navaratnam K.
A1  - Ankers D.
A1  - Sharma S.D. 
Y1  - 2011//
N2  - Introduction: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a prevalent endocrine disorder affecting 5%- 10% of women of reproductive age. Subfertility with PCOS is attributable both to ovulatory dysfunction and hyperandrogenism. Successful ovulation induction can be achieved with weight loss, Clomiphene citrate (CC), Metformin, Gonadotrophins and Laparoscopic Ovarian Drilling (LOD). CC is the conventional first-line ovulation induction agent for PCOS. In cases of CC-resistant PCOS, laparoscopic ovarian drilling (LOD) can be a productive alternative. LOD has decreased risk of ovarian hyper stimulation, multiple pregnancies and miscarriage compared to CC. LOD involves bilateral or unilateral, laser or electrical drilling of ovarian surface altering ovarian androgen production. For CC-resistant PCOS, LOD produces spontaneous ovulation in 30-90% of women and 13-88% of women conceive. The mechanism of action appears to be reduction of serum androgen production. Concomitantly, LOD promotes significant falls in luteinising hormone (LH) and insulin. Patients with demonstrable decreases in testosterone and LH are more likely to ovulate. Women with CC-resistant PCOS, who do not achieve ovulation after LOD, often become responsive to CC following ovarian drilling. Material(s) and Method(s): Retrospective case note audit Time Period: 5 years LOD was offered as first-line treatment to women with PCOS having a BMI 25, with or without hyperandrogenism or raised LH. Patients were counselled regarding the risks associated with LOD, possible decline in ovarian reserve, adhesion formation and laparoscopic surgical risks and the treatment-specific risks of alternative ovulation induction methods such as ovarian hyperstimulation, multiple pregnancy and increased miscarriage rate. Intervention(s): Diagnostic laparoscopy with or without dye testing prior to ovarian drilling with bipolar diathermy; 4 holes were made in each ovary with depth of 3-4 mm. Standards: Ovulation Induction in Polycystic Ovaries-Clinical guideline 2010 (Council of the Society of Obstetricians & Gynaecologists of Canada. 2010). Laparoscopic drilling by diathermy or laser for ovulation induction in anovulatory polycystic ovary syndrome (Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews 2007). Result(s): 43 patients were identified meeting the Rotterdam criteria for PCOS. 79% of women were aged 25-35 years, 72% were nulliparous and 65% had a normal BMI. All women had tubal patency testing; 91% had laparoscopy and dye testing at the time of LOD and 9% had hysterosalpingogram prior to LOD. 91% of men had evidence of semen analysis prior to LOD. 55 % patients conceived following LOD; the optimal time for achieving pregnancy was 0-9 months. 75% of women, who conceived with LOD, had a normal BMI (BMI 18.5- 24), 17% were overweight (BMI 25-29) and 8% were underweight (BMI < 18.5). 44% of women did not conceive with LOD including 3 women who tried CC prior to ovarian drilling. 89% tried CC after unsuccessful ovarian drilling; 18% conceived, 29% went on to receive gonadotrophins, 1 couple underwent IUI but all these methods were unsuccessful. Conclusion(s): LOD is effective and may be considered as first-line treatment in PCOS for women with a normal BMI. It can be combined with laparoscopy dye testing thus reducing laparoscopic procedures. Careful patient selection and informed patient choice is crucial. The risks of CC should be balanced against those of LOD including the potential impact on ovarian reserve. Risks and the success rates of each method should form a basis for counselling the couple. Local guidance should be updated to reflect these results and a LOD care pathway be developed with re-audit in three years. Research to assess Anti Mullerian Hormone levels prior to and following LOD is vital to delineate the effect on ovarian reserve. A Randomised Control Trial should be undertaken to compare CC and LOD as a first line ovulation induction method for women with PCOS and normal BMI.
