435. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 29151204
T1  - Satellite in vitro fertilization: A French experience
A1  - Hocke C.
A1  - Pasquet S.
A1  - Papaxanthos A.
A1  - Laurent E.
A1  - Duluco M.C.
A1  - Chene G.
A1  - Marmie S.
A1  - Mayer G.
A1  - Leng J.J. 
Y1  - 1999//
N2  - Objective: To evaluate the possibility of introducing a satellite system permitting ovary induction before oocyte retrieval for in vitro fertilization (IVF) in local cities in the southwest of France without change in pregnancy results. Advantages of the program included access for local residents to new IVF technologies and better comfort for patients. Design(s): The study was retrospective and enrolled all IVF attempts from December 1992 to December 1993. Method(s): Ovarian stimulation was adapted and monitored locally, using ultrasonography and estradiol dosage. After adequate stimulation, patients were referred to the principal center for oocyte retrieval and embryo transfer. Pregnancy was defined by ultrasonography or human chorionic gonadotropin level over 1000 UI. Variables studied were satellite city, ovulatory state, indication, stimulation rank, protocol type, gonadotropin regimen, administered human menopausal gonadotropin (hMG) or follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), oocyte number, total embryos obtained, and number transferred. Univariate analysis was performed (chi-square, Fisher's exact test, and Student's t-test) and completed by a multivariable analysis with logistic regression to control for variables. Result(s): During this period, 308 IVF attempts were performed (224 inductions from Bordeaux, 84 from satellite cities). Mean age of subjects was 32 years. Tubal damage was the most frequent indication for IVF (52%). Long protocols were frequently used (69%). The average number of oocytes retrieved was 9.3, average total embryos, 4.6; average transferred embryos, 2.3. Pregnancies rates were statistically different, with 22.6% in the principal center and 8.9% in satellites centers. On the univarate analysis, satellite city, indication, protocol type, number of oocytes retrieved, total number of embryos, and number of transferred embryos were associated with pregnancy results. Two of the four satellite centers had poor results, with a tendency to have older women, predominance of masculine indications, women with polycystic ovaries, and fewer embryos obtained. To eliminate these variable factors, a multivariate analysis was applied, and four variables remained statistically associated with success: the number of women (OR = 4.58, 95% CI = 1.56-13.44), heterologous IVF (OR = 1.45, 95% CI = 1.57-3.71), total embryos obtained (OR = 1.1, 95% CI = 1.0-1.12), number of embryos transferred (OR = 1.4, 95% CI = 1.05-1.87). Conclusion(s): After control for variables, four remained significantly associated with rate of pregnancy. Satellite induction seems to be associated with poor results. If the IVF Satellite Center Program is to continue, there needs to be better communication between the central unit and the satellite treatment centers.
